<item>
            <title>[GROOVY-3522] keyStrokeAction shouldn&apos;t presume text is a shortcut</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-3522</link>
                <project id="12318123" key="GROOVY">Groovy</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;The following code is meant to call the tweet action when the user presses ENTER&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;keyStrokeAction(component:tweetBox, keyStroke:&lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&quot;ENTER&quot;&lt;/span&gt;, action: controller.tweetAction)
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But instead the SwingBuilder binds the action to (on windows) CTRL+ENTER and (on mac) Opt+ENTER.  This is suprising.  If the user wants them to be shortcuts then they  would sepecify &lt;tt&gt;keyStroke:shortcut(&quot;ENTER&quot;)&lt;/tt&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
